1 AN ACT concerning education; relating to school district accreditation;
2 requiring school districts to demonstrate improvement in academic
3 performance and be in compliance with federal and state statutes and
4 rules and regulations to achieve or maintain accreditation; amending
5 K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-5170 and repealing the existing section; also
6 repealing K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-5170a.
7
8 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the State of Kansas:
9 Section 1. K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-5170 is hereby amended to read as
10 follows: 72-5170. (a) (1) In order to accomplish the mission for Kansas
11 education constitutional mandate of intellectual, educational, vocational
12 and scientific improvement, the state board shall design and adopt a school
13 district accreditation system based upon that requires conclusive,
14 measurable evidence of improvement in student academic performance
15 that and equals or exceeds the educational goal set forth in K.S.A. 72-
16 3218(c), and amendments thereto, and is measurable. Beginning July 1,
17 2026, and each school year thereafter, to achieve or maintain
18 accreditation, school districts shall demonstrate material improvement in
19 student academic performance from the preceding school year, evidenced
20 by a significant reduction in the number of students who scored at level 1
21 on state assessments and a significant increase in the number of students
22 who scored above level 2 on state assessments, pursuant to rules and
23 regulations adopted by the state board. The state board shall hold all
24 school districts and each public school operated by such school districts
25 accountable through the Kansas education systems accreditation rules and
26 regulations, or any successor accreditation system and accountability
27 measures plan adopted by the state board. The state board also shall set
28 required academic performance improvement targets and ensure that all
29 school districts and the public schools operated by such districts have
30 programs and initiatives in place for providing those educational capacities
31 set forth in K.S.A. 72-3218(c), and amendments thereto. On or before
32 January 15 of each year, the state board shall prepare and submit a report
33 on the school district accreditation system to the governor and the
34 legislature.
35 (2) The accountability measures established pursuant to paragraph (1)
36 shall be applied both at the district level and at the school level. Such

SB 48 2
1 accountability measures shall be reported by the state board for each
2 school district and each school. All reports prepared pursuant to this
3 section shall be published in accordance with K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-1181,
4 and amendments thereto.
5 (3) The school district accreditation system shall require school
6 districts and public schools operated by such school districts to be in
7 compliance with all applicable federal and state statutes and rules and
8 regulations. School districts and schools that are found to be out of
9 compliance with one or more applicable federal and state statutes and
10 rules and regulations shall be notified by the state board of such
11 noncompliance. Any such notification shall identify the nature and extent
12 of noncompliance and provide a deadline for the noncompliance to be
13 corrected. Such deadline shall not extend beyond June 30 of the
14 succeeding school year. Failure of a school district to correct the
15 noncompliance by the established deadline shall result in the loss of the
16 school district's accreditation. The notice of noncompliance shall be
17 posted on the state board's website and prominently posted on the
18 homepage of such school district's website until the noncompliance has
19 been corrected. The state board shall establish a due process procedure to
20 allow a school district, public school or individual to challenge a
21 determination of compliance.
22 (4) If a school district is conditionally accredited, accredited with
23 conditions or otherwise not fully accredited and, the state board shall
24 require a corrective action plan is required, which shall be approved by the
25 state board,. Such corrective action plan, and any subsequent reports
26 prepared by the state board regarding the progress of such school district
27 in implementing and executing such corrective action plan, shall be
28 published on the state department of education's internet website and such
29 school district's internet website in accordance with K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-
30 1181, and amendments thereto.
31 (4)(5) If a school district is not fully accredited for failure to
32 demonstrate conclusive, measurable evidence of improvement in student
33 academic performance as required by paragraph (1), the superintendent,
34 or the superintendent's designee, shall appear before the committee on
35 education of the house of representatives and the committee on education
36 of the senate during the regular legislative session that occurs during the
37 same school year in which when such school district is not accredited.
38 Such school district shall provide a report to such committees on the
39 challenges and obstacles that are preventing such school district from
40 becoming fully accredited and what actions, including, but not limited to,
41 reallocation of school district resources, are being taken or will be taken
42 to correct its unaccredited status.
43 (b) The state board shall establish curriculum standards that reflect

SB 48 3
1 high academic standards for the core academic areas of mathematics,
2 science, reading, writing and social studies. The curriculum standards shall
3 may be reviewed at least every seven years. The state board shall not
4 substantially revise or update the English language arts or mathematics
5 curriculum standards that are in effect on July 1, 2024, in a manner that
6 would necessitate the development of new statewide assessments in
7 English language arts or mathematics until the state board's long-term
8 goal for all students submitted to the United States department of
9 education in the consolidated state plan is achieved such that 75% of all
10 students score in performance levels 3 and 4 combined on the statewide
11 assessments in English language arts and mathematics by 2030. Nothing
12 in this subsection shall be construed in any manner so as to impinge upon
13 any school district's authority to determine its own curriculum if the school
14 district's curriculum reflects high academic standards.
15 (c) (1) The state board shall provide for statewide assessments in the
16 core academic areas of mathematics, science, reading, writing and social
17 studies. The board shall ensure compatibility between the statewide
18 assessments and the curriculum standards established pursuant to
19 subsection (b). Such assessments shall be administered at three grade
20 levels, as determined by the state board. The state board shall determine
21 performance levels on the statewide assessments, the achievement of
22 which represents high academic standards in the academic area at the
23 grade level to which the assessment applies. The state board should shall
24 specify high academic standards both for individual performance and
25 school performance on the assessments.
26 (2) (A) On or before January 15 of each year, the state board shall
27 prepare and submit to the legislature a report on students who take the
28 statewide assessments. Such report shall include:
29 (i) The number of students and such number expressed as a
30 percentage of the total number of students who took the statewide
31 assessments during the immediately preceding school year disaggregated
32 by core academic area and by grade level; and
33 (ii) the percentage of students who took the statewide assessments in
34 grade 10 who, two years after graduating from high school, obtained some
35 postsecondary education disaggregated by statewide assessment
36 achievement level.
37 (B) When such information becomes available, or as soon thereafter
38 as practicable, the state board shall publish the information required for the
39 report under subparagraph (A) on the website of the state department of
40 education and incorporate such information in the performance
41 accountability reports and longitudinal achievement reports required under
42 K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-5178, and amendments thereto.
43 (C) The provisions of this paragraph shall expire on July 1, 2029.

