1 (d) Each school year, on such date as specified by the state board,
2 each school district shall submit the Kansas education system accreditation
3 report to the state board in such form and manner as prescribed by the state
4 board.
5 (e) Whenever the state board determines that a school district has
6 failed either to meet the accreditation requirements established in this
7 section, by rules and regulations or standards adopted by the state board or
8 provide curriculum based on state standards and courses required by state
9 law, the state board shall so notify the school district. Such notice shall
10 specify the accreditation requirements that the school district has failed to
11 meet and, if applicable, the curriculum that it has failed to provide. Upon
12 receipt of such notice, the board of education of such school district is
13 encouraged to reallocate shall address the deficiencies identified by the
14 state board, including, if applicable, reallocation of the resources of the
15 school district to remedy all such deficiencies identified by the state board.
16 (f) Each school in every school district shall establish a school site
17 council composed of the principal and representatives of teachers and
18 other school personnel, parents of students attending the school, the
19 business community and other community groups. School site councils
20 shall be responsible for providing advice and counsel in evaluating state,
21 school district, and school site performance goals and objectives and in
22 determining the methods that should be employed at the school site to
23 meet these goals and objectives, including, but not limited to, participation
24 in the building-based needs assessment process required by K.S.A. 72-
25 1163, and amendments thereto. Site councils may make recommendations
26 and proposals to the school board regarding budgetary items and school
27 district matters, including, but not limited to, identifying and implementing
28 the best practices for developing efficient and effective administrative and
29 management functions. Site councils also may help school boards analyze
30 the unique environment of schools, enhance the efficiency and maximize
31 limited resources, including outsourcing arrangements and cooperative
32 opportunities as a means to address limited budgets.
33 Sec. 2. K.S.A. 2024 Supp. 72-5170 and 72-5170a are hereby
34 repealed.
35 Sec. 3. This act shall take effect and be in force from and after its
36 publication in the statute book.

